	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">This Body</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sy-safransky">Sy Safransky</a></li><li><a href="/issues/193">December 1991</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p class="dropcap">My daughters want to know why I&rsquo;ve started working out at the Y. I want bigger muscles, I tell them. I want to be stronger. They think this is hilarious: a forty-six-year-old man acting like he&rsquo;s sixteen.</p>

<p>But at sixteen, I acted like I was forty-six. I began college that year and was too busy for sports, too serious. A couple of decades later, I took up running, which is terrific for endurance but did nothing for my flabby middle, my shoulders, my arms, my chest.</p>

<p>My daughters still don&rsquo;t get it. To them, my body is familiar, predictable, a fixed star in the firmament of middle age. It&rsquo;s a father&rsquo;s body, sour with the sweats of work and worry, strong enough.</p>

<p>What difference does it make how I look? Instead of straining to do one more overhead press, I could be at the Columbia Street Bakery, drinking coffee and reading the newspaper. I could be nibbling on a bran muffin or &mdash; life is short &mdash; a raspberry-chocolate croissant, instead of getting right up in gravity&rsquo;s face, adding ten more pounds to the bar.</p>

<p>The eight Nautilus machines face a wall-to-wall mirror in a windowless room. With their creaking cams and chains, they look like they belong in a medieval dungeon. In this more secular age, we torture ourselves.</p>

<p>My interrogator eyes me coolly. <em>I won&rsquo;t deny it</em>, I say. <em>I&rsquo;m goaded by vanity. I tried to love my body. All those years of psychotherapy. It was like trying to love spinach.</em> He lights a cigarette. <em>I figured maybe I&rsquo;d love myself more if I looked better.</em> He raises an eyebrow. <em>OK, I admit, that&rsquo;s not real love.</em> He nods. <em>But it feels great: the body called from slumber, a troubled dream of irrelevance, fat replaced by muscle, arms and chest taking on a more defined shape.</em> Very good, he says. Two more sets, he says. And remember, he says, you don&rsquo;t build strength by repeating easy movements. Once you can overcome the resistance, increase the resistance. When you work at the limit of your strength, you force the muscle to adapt.</p>

<p>This is a metaphor for life, I think. What&rsquo;s that line from <a href="/contributors/rainer-maria-rilke">Rilke</a>? <em>The purpose of life is to be defeated by greater and greater things.</em> But I spend enough time thinking. I&rsquo;m here to work the lower back and the abdominals, not to think. I&rsquo;m here to do the duo squat, the leg curl, the pullover, the arm cross, the decline press, the lateral raise, the overhead press, the arm extension, the arm curl. I&rsquo;m here because my ancestors were large, heavily muscled animals, who for millions of years ran down other animals for food, while I sit at a desk all day, running down fleeting thoughts. I&rsquo;m here because I&rsquo;m estranged from my body, rarely knowing myself through dint of hard work. I&rsquo;m here because when I was a kid, I asked for a set of weights and got a lecture instead about how weight lifters are muscle-bound, not to mention stupid and conceited. Was my father threatened that I might become stronger than he was?</p>

<p><em>Cut the crap</em>, my interrogator warns. <em>You&rsquo;re here because you&rsquo;re a privileged white male, who can afford to workout instead of work. You&rsquo;re here, spending too much time resting between sets, while real men &mdash; and real women, too &mdash; are getting out of bed, groggily getting dressed, and shuffling off to a day of real work.</em></p>

<p>The people here are real enough for me. There&rsquo;s the burly truck driver who boasts, not long after the Gulf War, that his son has joined the Air Force. There&rsquo;s the house painter who chides me when I change the dial from the rock station to National Public Radio. There&rsquo;s the Vietnam vet who scolds me for not breathing right: exhale during the pressing part of the lift, he warns, inhale on the return. Momentarily confused, I forget to breathe altogether. He shakes his head. And don&rsquo;t forget to breathe, he sighs.</p>

<p>But we don&rsquo;t talk much. I&rsquo;m here to exercise my body, not my big mouth. I&rsquo;m here to stop being bullied by the past, to stop making excuses, to stop pretending on hot summer days that it&rsquo;s not really hot enough to strip off my shirt.</p>

<p>Of course, there are mornings I don&rsquo;t show up at all, when I&rsquo;m too busy or too depressed, when I don&rsquo;t want to look like another middle-aged man trying to stop the inevitable ruin of his body. Time has already taken a couple of bites; it likes the taste. But the next morning I&rsquo;m back, winking in the mirror at the fool who&rsquo;s determined to be lean, tough, and chewy before time licks the plate.</p>
														</div>


				
